Project Objective 

The objective of this project is to develop a convolutional neural network (CNN) model using the ResNet-50 architecture to detect glaucoma from retinal fundus images in the REFUGE V1 dataset. 

  

The REFUGE V1 dataset is a publicly available dataset of 1200 high-quality retinal fundus images from patients with and without glaucoma. The images have been annotated with ground truth segmentations of the optic disc and optic cup, as well as clinical glaucoma labels. 

  

The project will involve the following steps: 

  

Data preprocessing: The REFUGE V1 dataset will be preprocessed to ensure that all images are of the same size and format. 

Data Augmentation: The REFUGE V1 dataset is imbalanced towards the Non-Glaucoma Class, Data augmentation is used to up-sample the Glaucoma class images to avoid overfitting. 

Model training: The ResNet-50 model will be trained on the REFUGE V1 dataset to learn to distinguish between glaucomatous and non-glaucomatous images. 

Model evaluation: The trained model will be evaluated on a separate test set of retinal fundus images to assess its performance. 

Model explainability: GradCAM technique is used understand and visualize the most valuable feature area in the input image developed by the model. 

Contributions 

This project will make the following contributions to the field of glaucoma detection: 

Develop a CNN model using the ResNet-50 architecture that is specifically designed for glaucoma detection. 

Evaluate the performance of the CNN model on a large, publicly available dataset of retinal fundus images. 

Make the trained CNN model and its evaluation results publicly available to the research community. 

 
